{
  "answer": "**The work is the *Gaṇapatitattva* (by Unknown), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThe two ślokas in question appear toward the end of the chapter (verses 54–55), teaching the five-syllable mantra *Pañcakāṇḍa* (*jaḥ, taḥ, kiḥ, uṃ, phaṭ*) with the specified element-to-syllable mapping, for the destruction of great sins and attainment of Śiva's world:\n\n> In the syllable *jaḥ*, earth is to be known; in the syllable *taḥ*, the waters are established.  \n> In the syllable *kiḥ* is the great fire; in the syllable *uṃ*, one should place the wind. // (54)[^2]\n\n> Joined with the syllable *phaṭ* for the ether, for the destruction of great sins.  \n> He who, being wise, recites the *Pañcāṇḍa*, attains the world of Śiva. // (55)[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-570c4a).\n\n[^3]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-bb1220).",
